Marcus Smart brought a special guest to the Celtics’ Christmas Day game: 19-year-old, Justice – whom he met through Be The Match – an organization that helps patients get life saving transplants. Justice has sickle cell disease and every day, he has to work to manage his chronic pain. He is waiting for a blood stem cell transplant. Smart got involved in Be The Match when he lost his brother and mother to cancer. Smart’s goal is to continue to educate people – especially about the black community — because only 7 percent of the 9 million donors in the Be A Match registration are African American, according the the website. Marcus and Justice have become friends. They text and have visited each other’s home. Smart told me: “It’s people like Justice who inspire me to work hard and continue advocating for such an important cause. I’m grateful our paths have crossed.”
